[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    212[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The Bedrock paragraph correctly names the productivity-tool framing ("Always as a productivity tool, never as a decision-maker, and always with human review attached") and includes the right HTML-comment TODO acknowledging that the HIPAA-eligible Bedrock model list shifts. The Step 8 pseudocode uses [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mmodel_id = "anthropic.claude-XX"[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m which is appropriately abstract about the specific Anthropic version. But the BAA-discipline forward reference that Chapter 2's recipes (especially 2.4-2.10) settled is missing: Bedrock with Amazon Titan models is HIPAA-eligible under the BAA; third-party models on Bedrock (Anthropic Claude, Meta Llama, Cohere, AI21) have different BAA postures and the model's terms of service must be reviewed before PHI-bearing prompts are sent. The recipe's "HIPAA-eligible LLMs" phrasing doesn't differentiate. Also missing: minimum-necessary prompt construction (the prompt should not carry the entire chart; it should carry only the relevant note excerpts, the flagged claim, and the relevant coverage policy), output filtering for clinical-recommendation hallucinations (an LLM that says "this provider is committing fraud" rather than "the documentation does not support the billed code" produces evidentiary problems), and a full prompt-and-response audit trail that ties to the case ID for evidence-of-decision. Same finding shape as Recipes 3.3 V2, 3.4 S4, 3.5 S5.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    213[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mFix:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Expand the Bedrock paragraph: "Bedrock with Amazon foundation models is HIPAA-eligible under the BAA; third-party models on Bedrock (Anthropic Claude, Meta Llama, others) have differing BAA postures, and the model's terms of service must be reviewed before PHI-bearing prompts are sent. Construct prompts with minimum-necessary context (relevant note excerpts, the flagged claim, and the applicable coverage policy; not the full chart). Filter outputs for clinical-recommendation language: the LLM should produce documentation-assessment language ('the documentation does not support the billed level-5 office visit because the chief complaint and history-of-present-illness sections do not establish a complexity tier 4 medical decision-making') rather than legal-conclusion language ('this is fraud'). Log every prompt and response to the audit trail tied to the case ID; the prompt-response pair is part of the evidence-of-decision in the case file. See Chapter 2's generative AI recipes for the established BAA discipline." Add a forward reference to the Chapter 2 recipes that established this pattern.[K
