[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    280[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    281[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mStream-normalizer Lambda fails on a malformed message.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The clearinghouse emits an unexpected 837 segment (rare but happens with new payer-specific extensions), the LOINC or CPT code is not in the lookup table (codes change quarterly with CCI updates), the entity-resolution call to NPPES times out. Lambda's default async retry behavior is two retries over six hours and then drop. The result is silently lost: no canonical claim reaches the rules layer, no flags fire on that claim, the claim flows through adjudication without screening. For a system whose value proposition is catching fraud-bearing claims, silently-failing ingestion is the worst possible failure mode.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    282[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    283[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mRules-engine Lambda fails during rule evaluation[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m (DynamoDB throttle on the patient-context-cache, S3 read timeout on the rule library, exclusion-check API timeout). Same retry-then-drop pattern. The claim passes through unscored. For a claim that should have triggered a critical rule (post-mortem billing, billing-by-excluded-entity), this is exactly the failure mode the system is meant to catch.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    284[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
