[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    522[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m The NPI (National Provider Identifier) is a 10-digit number with a check-digit that uses the Luhn algorithm with a fixed prefix of "80840" (per CMS NPPES specification). The sample "1234567890" does not check-digit-validate (running Luhn on "8084012345678" produces a check digit of 5, not 0). Same for "9988776655" (does not validate). For a recipe about FWA detection, where one of the central detection clues is identifier-integrity checks (post-mortem billing under a deceased provider's NPI, billing under an excluded provider's NPI, billing under stolen credentials), using a non-validating NPI in the sample output is a domain-accuracy ding. A reader who copies the sample for testing or who tries to demonstrate the pipeline against the sample will produce a system that erroneously rejects the synthetic claim because the NPI doesn't validate, or worse, will assume the validation is not part of the pipeline.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    523[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
