[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    549[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mPattern: A1 (outcome-event idempotency) is the now-recurring trigger-idempotency finding, surfacing for the twelfth consecutive recipe (2.4-2.10 and 3.1-3.6).[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m Same fix template (deterministic event-key derivation, conditional-write enforcement at the orchestration layer), different specific event source (flag events from four detectors here). For Recipe 3.6 the consequence is calibrated to the regulatory-referral pathway: doubled priority scores from redelivered flag events can flip cases from "investigation only" to "regulatory referral" or vice versa, and the timing and accuracy of the referral is itself a compliance posture under 42 CFR 422.504(h) and 438.608. With this finding now flagged across twelve consecutive recipes, the cookbook editor should treat the trigger-idempotency appendix as the highest-leverage cookbook-wide editorial investment.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    550[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    551[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mPattern: A2 (DLQ / poison-message handling) is operationally critical for Recipe 3.6 specifically because flag outputs feed compliance-mandated regulatory referrals.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m A dropped event in the rules-engine path is a missed flag on a claim that may have a critical-rule violation (post-mortem billing, billing-by-excluded-entity); a dropped event in the evidence-aggregator path is a case that never gets built; a dropped event in the outcome-capture path is a case-disposition that never gets recorded for FCA-exposure documentation. The DLQ-depth alarm threshold for the stream-normalizer path should be 1, and DLQ replay older than the regulatory-referral compliance window should escalate to compliance-team review rather than auto-replay.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    552[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    553[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mPattern: S1 (graph-construction patient-node-ID inconsistency and missing claim vertices) is a teaching-fidelity bug with operational consequences.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m Unlike the prose-vs-pseudocode asymmetries in A3 (provider appeals workflow), A4 (reference-data versioning), A5 (suppression expiry), A6 (drift monitoring), A7 (rule change management), this is a code-level inconsistency where the pseudocode contradicts itself (comment says "organization -> claim" but code goes "organization -> hashed-patient"). For a recipe whose biggest pedagogical contribution is the graph-is-the-secret-sauce subsection, the graph-construction example needs to be internally consistent. The fix pattern (add claim vertices, separate the rendered-on-claim and billed-for-claim and for-patient edge types) is editorially substantive but the corrected pseudocode then supports the high-value queries the recipe's prose describes.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    554[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    555[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mPattern: A3 (provider appeals), A4 (reference-data versioning propagation), A5 (suppression expiry enforcement), A6 (drift monitoring primitives), A7 (rule change management primitives) are all the same prose-vs-pseudocode asymmetry shape as Recipes 3.4 A3 and 3.5 A3-A6.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m The recipe's Honest Take and Why This Isn't Production-Ready sections call out specific disciplines that the canonical pseudocode walkthrough doesn't reflect. For Recipe 3.6 specifically, the prose emphasis is unusually high (the appeals workflow is a regulatory-due-process concern; the reference-data versioning is a regulatory-referral-evidence concern; the suppression-expiry is an FCA-exposure concern; the drift monitoring is an investigator-throughput concern; the rule change management is a CCI-quarterly-update concern). A reader who treats the pseudocode as the implementation specification produces systems that exhibit exactly the failure modes the prose warns against in five different domains.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    556[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    557[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mPattern: S2 (SNS/EventBridge notification PHI minimization) is the now-recurring PHI-minimization-inside-the-BAA pattern with the seventh distinct surface across the cookbook[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m (Chapter 2: serialized prompt context; Recipe 3.1: examiner free-text reasoning; Recipe 3.2: patient-facing reminder content for high-stigma specialties; Recipe 3.3: internal SNS notification payload; Recipe 3.4: SNS interrupt-alert payload with high-stigma drug-class disclosure; Recipe 3.5: SNS critical-callback payload with high-stigma test-class disclosure; Recipe 3.6: case-ready-for-triage notification with provider-and-flag-detail sensitivity, including post-mortem-billing flag content carrying patient date of death and ownership-cascade flag content carrying corporate-officer information). The underlying discipline is identical (don't carry sensitive information through stores or messages you don't need it in), but the surface has shifted again. For Recipe 3.6 the specific concern is that flag content is itself sensitive in ways that go beyond per-patient PHI: a flag on a provider-exclusion violation is sensitive provider information; a kickback-cascade flag exposes corporate-officer information; the per-investigator-tier-of-access discipline matters across all three. A cookbook-wide PHI-minimization appendix would consolidate all seven surfaces with one teaching pass.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    558[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    559[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mPattern: S3 (subgroup data governance) is the same finding shape as Recipes 3.2 S2, 3.3 S2, 3.4 S2, 3.5 S2 (now five recipes deep).[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m All five recipes correctly identify the need for subgroup monitoring; all five correctly defer the "what data is captured" question to the operational team; all five leave the architectural artifacts that make subgroup monitoring binding (data store location, access scope, audit trail, query path) unspecified. Recipe 3.6's distinctive consideration is that provider race/ethnicity is itself a subgroup dimension whose historical pattern of disproportionate enforcement in FWA contexts is well-documented, and case-mix adjustment (the recipe's correct mitigation for legitimate practice variation) requires patient-level demographic data joined to provider attribution that needs governance. With this finding now flagged across five chapter-3 recipes, the subgroup-governance appendix is a high-leverage cookbook-wide editorial investment alongside trigger-idempotency.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    560[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    561[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mPattern: S4 (legal-privilege architecture infrastructure primitives) is unique to Recipe 3.6.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m Recipes 2.4-2.10, 3.1-3.5 don't carry this concern because the underlying systems are operating in standard PHI-handling environments without privileged-investigation overlay. Recipe 3.6's prose framing is correct ("coordinate with the general counsel before architectural decisions") but does not give the architect the infrastructure primitives to bring to that conversation. The fix (separate AWS account, separate VPC, separate KMS keys, distinct CloudTrail trail, SCP-level controls) gives the architect a starting point for the GC conversation. This is the single most distinctive finding in the recipe and the editorial fix has high leverage because it equips first-time builders to have an informed legal-privilege conversation rather than walking in with no specific proposals.[K
