[38;5;141m> [0m{"verdict": "pass", "rationale": "Recipe 3.6 (Healthcare FWA Detection) demonstrates strong clinical accuracy, architectural soundness, security posture, and operational realism. It passes review with the prioritized findings below.\n\nCLINICAL ACCURACY: Legal citations are correct (42 USC 1320a-7b Anti-Kickback; 42 USC 1395nn Stark; 31 USC 3729-3733 FCA; 42 CFR 422.504(h), 438.608, 411.354; 45 CFR 164.512(f)). Scheme taxonomy (phantom billing, upcoding, unbundling, medically unnecessary, kickbacks, identity theft, collusive networks, patient-side abuse, billing mills) aligns with OIG enforcement patterns. CPT/E&M codes (99211-99215), modifier 59, CCI, MUE, NCDs/LCDs, LEIE, PECOS, NPPES, Sunshine Act used correctly. NHCAA ~3%/$100B figure is appropriately TODO-flagged.\n\nARCHITECTURAL SOUNDNESS: Layered Rules+Statistical+Graph+ML detection is industry best practice. Service selection is well-justified: Neptune+Neptune ML for relationship graph, OpenSearch k-NN for embedding similarity, DynamoDB for low-latency case state, SageMaker Feature Store for point-in-time correctness, Clarify for fairness, Comprehend Medical+Bedrock for documentation review, Clean Rooms for cross-payer. Pseudocode is internally consistent and illustrative.\n\nSECURITY: KMS CMK on all PHI stores, TLS 1.2+, VPC endpoints, Neptune/OpenSearch in VPC, CloudTrail data events, separate logging account with SCPs, hashed patient IDs in graph properties, Secrets Manager, least-privilege IAM, BAA scope identified.\n\nHIDDEN CHALLENGES: 'Why This Isn't Production-Ready,' 'Where It Struggles,' and 'The Honest Take' sections reflect deep operational experience (entity resolution as multi-quarter project, investigator capacity as the binding constraint, label latency/self-confirming bias, adversarial adaptation cycles, peer-group iteration, case management as 60% of value, fairness/equity monitoring, change management for rule releases, provider appeals/due process).\n\nPRIORITIZED FINDINGS:\n\nHIGH-1 (Authorization mediation in graph access): Mermaid shows Neptune (Q) wired directly to AppSync (AB), implying client access without per-investigator scope checks. Remediation: insert explicit AppSync resolver Lambdas that enforce case-assignment-based authorization on Gremlin queries; document that AppSync does not bind directly to Neptune for PHI workloads.\n\nHIGH-2 (Patient ID hashing semantics): hash_patient_id is referenced without specifying construction. Remediation: require HMAC keyed with a KMS CMK, document key rotation impact on graph identity continuity, and confirm raw subscriber/member IDs never enter Neptune node properties or OpenSearch case index outside encrypted blob fields.\n\nHIGH-3 (Separation of duties and break-glass): Audit trail is covered, but procedural controls (preventing the same investigator from flagging and unilaterally closing high-dollar cases, supervisor approval for dismissals/suppressions, break-glass for urgent law-enforcement coordination) are not specified. Remediation: add a SoD subsection in the case management workflow with explicit role boundaries and time-bounded break-glass with mandatory CloudTrail review.\n\nMEDIUM-1 (Bedrock guardrails): Documentation-assist invokes Bedrock without referencing Bedrock Guardrails. Remediation: require Guardrails configuration for PHI redaction in prompts, prompt-injection mitigation on chart text, and output filtering; pair with prompt versioning in Git.\n\nMEDIUM-2 (Rules-as-code operational design): CCI/MUE/medical-necessity rule library is declared but lifecycle management is described only narratively. Remediation: specify DMN/Drools-as-code in Git with PR review by certified coders, shadow-mode deployment against historical claims, and rollback playbook before listing rule_id in flag payloads.\n\nMEDIUM-3 (Cost estimate completeness): $5K-16K/month for a 30M-claims/year payer likely understates Neptune storage/IO at multi-year graph retention and excludes cross-region DR and external data subscriptions. Remediation: add Neptune Serverless evaluation, separate line for storage/IO scaling with graph size, and a DR multiplier (1.3-1.7x).\n\nMEDIUM-4 (Death Master File and PMP access): References to NTIS/SSA death data and state PMPs gloss over access mechanics. Remediation: clarify Limited Access DMF requires NTIS certification; PMP integration is state-by-state and typically intermediated by Appriss/Bamboo Health with separate BAAs.\n\nMEDIUM-5 (Reference repo naming inconsistency): Text cites 'amazon-neptune-samples' but links to graph-notebook. Remediation: standardize on the canonical aws/graph-notebook repository with the correct description, and reconcile the duplicate citation under Additional Resources.\n\nLOW-1 (Pseudocode disclaimer): Add a one-line note that S3.PutObject, Neptune.UpsertVertex, etc. are illustrative, not real SDK signatures.\nLOW-2 (PEPPER URL): Verify current host (PEPPER hosting has changed); update URL.\nLOW-3 (Recall benchmarks): 60-85% retrospective recall for full stack is at the optimistic end; either tighten to 40-70% or strengthen the 'illustrative' caveat with industry-baseline context.\nLOW-4 (Basic-tier timing): 6-10 months for rules + statistical + entity resolution + case management foundation is aggressive for organizations without prior payment-integrity infrastructure; widen to 8-14 months or add a prerequisite-state qualifier.\nLOW-5 (Breach notification): Add brief reference to HIPAA breach notification obligations if the case management system itself is compromised, given the heightened sensitivity of investigation work product.\nLOW-6 (Pre-payment integrity tradeoffs): The variation on real-time pre-payment integrity should mention prompt-payment-law constraints by state and the appeals burden created by denied-for-suspicion claims.\n\nThe TODO (TechWriter) markers throughout (NHCAA figures, HIPAA-eligible Bedrock models, GNN production references, healthcare-specific aws-samples, 